segments.text: We didn't see him too much socially, but I'm just basking in Frank's feelings of him, that he was the finest administrator that I've reckoned I've known.
Yeah, I think you certainly know that.
You know, all those people worked hard.
And Buck Weiris I remember worked hard, harder than anybody I knew.
Yeah, I was impressed with Buck.
And who was that guy who was in the library?
Buck Weiris, my man's gone too.
He was head of the library?
No, he had something to do with the library.
After he retired, he was hired on the part.
If it comes to the library.
Wouldn't Don die all or something?
He was always there for the students.
You can always tell a student-oriented professor knows you or not.
And I'm one of those who wasn't.
And I'll tell you, when you have 350 students in your classes, it's hard to think of anything else.
Well, you don't have to go to school anymore.
What would you like to tell me about your experiences at A&M?
Well, the key word is fun.
And that's what I see in Frank's letters.
Now also, I think I mentioned this.
He really was planning his retirement from the very first.
His letters are full of it.
I'm going to do this in memory.
It seemed to me he was there much longer.
It just seemed like so long.
And also Lloyd really took hold.
In fact, I learned a lot about Lloyd reading that correspondence.
And I'd say Lloyd and I were always good friends.
But I didn't know Lloyd was a good administrator.
He was right on top of it.
And Frank was a good lover.
I'm just so sorry that he got so ill so he couldn't write his memoirs.
It would have been wonderful if he did write his memoirs.
He told me a story here that he would go in on Sunday for a couple of hours and it would take his secretary
All day, Monday, he'd read his letters, what he had done on it.
He'd come in early in the morning, six o'clock.

Do you remember a lady named Jeanette Hennigan, who worked with him for a little while when you all first came to... Buck Wires gave me that name, and I haven't called her yet, but I don't remember her name.
Any other people that you remember interacting with particularly besides Bob Shewitz?
Haskell's coming back to College Station this summer.
He was an El Paso president.
Went to El Paso as president, then he went to Missouri as chancellor, whatever it was, and then stepped down.
Stayed up there, though, as a history professor.
for about four more years, and now he's come back.
And his son, he has one of his sons who's a doctor in Palm State.
In fact, we've been to him.
Yeah, now, see, Frank didn't come in, kind of thing, when he became president.
Jack Williams had a heart attack, you know.
And he kind of faded, and he came back for a while, and then retired, and then Vandiver came.
And Vandiver, I believe, had already gone.
Well, Frank was a friend of Vandiver's.
There are letters from Frank Vandiver to, between he and Wardlaw, 73 or 74 or something like that.
And I need to go talk to Frank.
I think from the time Frank was here, 1950.
I wouldn't be surprised because apparently Frank's father was a professor here.
Frank Bender is the only person I've ever heard of who skipped junior high and high school.
I don't even know if he ever got an undergraduate degree.
He didn't bother with all that other stuff.
He just got his Ph.D. and went on.
Still on the go around there.
I don't see him on the campus.
He can't get on the campus anymore.
I'm going to talk to him, because I know when he came in, he did a lot for the press.
And I know he didn't know.
I saw him bring in Black Jack, the Persian.
Make two trips up the stairs with his manuscript.
I'll remind Frank of that, of that moment.
What else can we talk about that would be interesting?
I guess, as far as you were concerned, there was no culture shock at Texas A&M.
Because that's what a lot of people say.
Well, I hadn't heard anything since having just come from Kansas.
I don't think I remember Maggie Joke when I came to Texas.
I don't believe they were around much until the 60s or 70s anyway.
Not even when I was here in Texas.
I do remember we often looked at that statue on the campus, which was constantly being painted.
And we would walk almost every night, and it would seem like every month they'd get another coat of paint on it.
They finally made them stop polishing so well, because they were polishing all the brass off.
So they had kind of stopped all that now.
I should have brought you a... Did you get a copy of that last...
I told Kayla to cease it.
Look, I've got all those books there from A&M.
To stop sending them, just sending these particular ones.
But anyway, in that book I saw Ross's statue.
They built a statue for General Rudder.
Oh, she was at, I went to a meeting.
She must have been a lot younger.
And I'm sure she may be pushing 80, but she looks good.
When she was at a meeting, we went to the Westerner's meeting last night.
And she was there in just great shape.
Anyway, she's been fussing at me because I...
In that picture book, that revision we did, we have Saul Ross's statue, but not Mr. Rutter's statue.
